{
  "query": "In Norway, how do different plant-based feed alternatives, such as vegetable oils versus plant proteins, affect salmon growth and body composition?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on Norwegian studies, plant-based protein alternatives show mixed effects on salmon growth and body composition compared to traditional fish meal. Action 924 reports that Norwegian studies found both decreased growth rates and similar growth rates in salmon fed plant-based protein diets, with some studies showing reduced final body weights while others found similar final body weights compared to fish meal diets. Feeding efficiency results were variable, with Norwegian studies finding both lowered and increased levels of feeding efficiency in salmon fed plant-based protein diets. Digestibility of plant proteins was found to be lower in some Norwegian studies, though similar levels of digestibility were identified in other Norwegian randomised, replicated, controlled studies. Plant-based protein diets altered the morphology of the distal intestine in salmon.\n\nIn contrast, vegetable oils show more consistent results. Action 926 indicates that Norwegian studies found growth rates were generally similar between salmon fed diets containing fish oil versus vegetable oil, with one Norwegian study actually finding higher growth rates in fish fed vegetable oil diets. Two Norwegian studies found similar average final body weights between salmon fed both fish oil and vegetable oil diets. However, the fatty acid profile of salmon flesh reflected the oil source within diets according to Norwegian and Scottish studies. One Norwegian study found that salmon fed vegetable oil diets had high liver lipid and low plasma lipoprotein compared to fish oil diets. Norwegian studies also found that fresh, frozen and smoked salmon flesh from fish fed vegetable oil- and fish oil-based diets had similar levels of gaping, texture and liquid holding capacity, though pigment concentration was lower in vegetable oil diets. Oil source did not affect salmon broodstock fecundity levels, egg weights, fertility rates, or the weights and development of resultant fry in Norwegian studies.",
  "action_ids": [
    "924",
    "926",
    "930"
  ]
}

